explanation:
For determining whether any operations in OS_GetResourceName are dead code (i.e., executed but removable without changing program behaviour) the analyzer must know the precise semantics, side-effects and possible return values of the symbols and data referenced by the function:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER
  - These macros/functions can short-circuit the function (e.g. by returning an error or asserting/aborting). If they abort or return, subsequent writes (such as buffer[0]=0) might be unreachable or redundant. Need definition to know whether their invocation makes preceding/following operations unnecessary.

- OS_CHECK_SIZE
  - Same rationale as OS_CHECK_POINTER: may validate buffer_size and cause early return/abort. Affects whether initial buffer initialization and later branches are actually executed/needed.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById
  - Central to control flow: returns return_code and populates token. Must know all possible return values, side effects (e.g. global locks, state changes) and whether it can always/never return OS_SUCCESS. This determines whether the entire success-path code (record access, copy, release) can ever execute and therefore whether any of it is dead.

- OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl
  - Converts object_id to a type used by OS_ObjectIdGetById. If this conversion can fail or produce special types that force OS_ObjectIdGetById to behave differently, that can make branches unreachable or redundant.

- OS_object_token_t
  - Token type populated by OS_ObjectIdGetById and consumed by OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken and OS_ObjectIdRelease. Its layout or semantics (e.g. invalid token value meaning nothing to release) are needed to know whether calls like OS_ObjectIdRelease are required (i.e. whether they have observable effects) or are removable.

- OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken
  - Produces the record pointer used to read the name. Need to know whether it can return NULL, whether the returned record is always valid, and whether it has side effects (e.g. pins object in memory). This affects whether the record->name_entry check and subsequent copy are ever meaningful.

- OS_common_record_t
  - Type definition (particularly the name_entry member) is required to know the valid range/semantics of name_entry (NULL vs empty string, lifetime, thread-safety). This decides if the name copy is necessary and whether checks on name_entry are redundant.

- record->name_entry
  - The field being tested and copied. Need to know if it can ever be NULL, whether it can point to an empty string, and whether reading it has side effects. This decides whether the whole inner block is potentially dead.

- OS_strnlen
  - Used to compute name_len with buffer_size limit. Need exact behavior (does it stop at buffer_size, return value range) to assess whether the subsequent branch (buffer_size <= name_len) can ever trigger and whether the computed name_len is meaningful; this affects whether the assignment to return_code = OS_ERR_NAME_TOO_LONG or the truncation is necessary.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - Value compared against return_code. Need to know its exact definition to evaluate the branch condition and whether the success path is reachable.

- OS_ERR_NAME_TOO_LONG
  - The function assigns this value inside the branch. To decide if that assignment is observable (i.e. changes what the caller sees), need the exact constant and whether other codepath assignments could override it. This helps determine whether that assignment is dead.

- memcpy
  - Performs the actual write to the user buffer. Knowing its semantics (standard memcpy) and whether the copied region may overlap with buffer or have other side effects is necessary to decide whether those writes are required for program behaviour.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease
  - Releases the token. Must know whether release has observable side-effects (releasing resources or unlocking) that affect global behaviour. If it is required (e.g. to avoid resource leaks or to change system state), removing it would change program behaviour; if it is a no-op in some configurations, it could be dead. 

Collectively these symbols determine whether each executed operation (initial buffer[0]=0, the conditional assignments to return_code, the memcpy, calls to release token, etc.) has observable effects on program behaviour and thus whether any of them constitute dead code.
